In a departure from my usual forecast format where I begin with a base rate, with is one I’m going to start from my conclusion and work backwards. The pro-democracy movement is widely expected to win the September legislative election. I fully concur with this assessment. Local elections in November saw them gain a huge majority in district councils and there is no reason to suspect that the Security Law has done anything but bolster that support as the island city descends further in chaos. [1]

The silent majority has screamed “hell yes!” to pro-democracy candidates at the local level and will continue to do so in the next legislative elections. This assumes the elections are held, which if Beijing has any say, they may very well not be.

The answer to this question is assuming the results of the election will be as announced by the Hong Kong authorities. After the Hong Kong primaries where 600,000 voted in an election deemed illegal by the Authorities for pro-democracy candidates where a more confrontational younger group displaced older democrats, Beijing has shown its displeasure. Candidates for the Legislative council must conform they will abide by article 6 of the new National Security Law. Companies and individuals have reducing their digital exposure to the authorities and would appear that Beijing is gaining the upper hand. My proposal is that Beijing wants to avoid a Tiananmen Square PR disaster and will forge ahead with the elections in September, but with hand selected candidates to ensure a victory for the mainland in its quest to amalgamate Hong Kong with China. This will guarantee a smooth transition incorporating the new national security law where dissidents will be transported to the Mainland and a sense of stable government be established. Pro-democracy candidates will not win a majority in Hong Kong’s Legislative Council based on the official announcement by the Hong Kong Authorities.

I am certain the election will be held as scheduled. For whatever reason covid19 is under control. I am unsure of Beijing's desire to manage the results. Letting the election run without Beijing management would most likely result in the Pro Democracy party gaining the majority. So this would let Beijinb signal to the world that the security law would not interfere with Hong Kong's self-governance. But it's the security law that the world is angry about because that represents infringement on self-governance. Reasons Beijing manages the results to prevent a pro-democracy majority 1)Trump may not be President in 2021 so consolidate while it can 2)already signaled a heavy hand with the security law 3)arrested persons under the security law 4) By awarding seats to loyalists the Party passes out favors. So since the security law is not going to be repealed there's nothing gained by signaling free elections equals self-governance. So I am more than 50 50 on the yes no split but not 100% certain.
